ly to understanding women religious and Catholicism in nineteenth-century England and Wales, but also to our understanding of the role of women in the public and private sphere, dealing with issues still resonant today. Contributing to the larger story of the agency of nineteenth-century women and the broader transformation of English society, this book will appeal to scholars and students of social, cultural, gender and religious history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMonasticism and religious orders for womenzEnglandxHistoryy19th century. 0aMonasticism and religious orders for womenzWalesxHistoryy19th century. 0aNunszEngland. 0aNunszWales. 7aRELIGION / Christian Life / General.2bisacsh  aCatholic women religious.  acontested identities.  acorporate identity.  aepiscopal authority.  aethnic background.  aevangelisers.  amiddle-class.  amissionary identity.  anineteenth-century England.  anineteenth-century Wales.  anovice mistress.  aprofessional identity.  areligious congregation.  areligious life.1 aMangion, Carmen M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152613528540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526135285423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526135285/original  a978-3-11-128363-0  Manchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagec1986d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles